{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Use British English|date=February 2018}} {{Infobox news event |title = <!-- Title to display, if other than page name --> |image = |image_name = |image_size = |caption = |time = 6:20 - 6:45 a.m. approx. |date= {{start date|1997|3|10|df=yes}} |place = [[Bromsgrove]], [[Worcestershire]], England |coordinates = |also known as = |first reporter = |filmed by = |participants = |outcome = |reported injuries = ~60 |reported death(s) = 3 |reported missing = |reported property damage = 160 vehicles damaged or destroyed; road surface scorched |burial = |inquiries = |inquest = |coroner = |suspects = |charges = |verdict = |convictions = David Fairclough, lorry driver (3 months, dangerous driving) |publication bans = |litigation = |awards = |url = |website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> |notes = }}
On 10 March 1997 a [[multiple-vehicle collision]] occurred on the [[M42 motorway]] near [[Bromsgrove]], [[Worcestershire]], in central England. Three people were killed and more than 60 others were injured in the crash, which happened in dense fog during the early morning rush hour.
At around 6:20 a.m. a [[truck|lorry]], driven by David Fairclough of Wednesfield, entered the M42 from a slip-road at a speed of {{convert|56|mph}} and, after slowing to {{convert|32|mph}}, rammed into the rear of a [[Tank truck|tanker]], which then struck a car in front and exploded. The ensuing pile-up involved 160 vehicles on a {{convert|400|yard|adj=on}} stretch of the motorway, including 30 on the opposite carriageway 20 minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Victim%27s+father+still+angry+as+M42+crash+driver+is+jailed.-a060538524|title=Victim's father still angry as M42 crash driver is jailed|last=Aitchison|first=Neil|publisher=The Birmingham Post|agency=Thefreelibrary.com|date=8 April 1999|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>
Five [[air ambulance]]s and 25 [[ambulance]]s ferried injured drivers and passengers from the scene to three hospitals. A [[police car]] was also involved in the pile-up; one firefighter responding to the crash criticised other motorists for overtaking his fire engine in excess of {{convert|70|mph}} in the dense fog. Several cars and lorries were burnt to a shell and more than 30 occupants had to be cut free from their vehicles by firefighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CARNAGE+IN+THE+FOG%3B+THREE+DIE+AND+62+HURT+IN+INFERNO+AS+100+VEHICLES...-a061109264|title=Carnage In The Fog: Three die and 62 hurt in inferno as 100 vehicles crash in tragic rush hour madness|last1=Chaytor|first1=Rod|last2=Miller|first2=Ian|publisher=The Mirror|agency=Thefreelibrary.com|date=11 March 1997|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>
Lisa Dodson, a 21-year-old student from [[Chaddesley Corbett]], was the driver of the car, a [[Peugeot 205]], struck by the tanker and she died from [[asphyxia]]tion. Malcolm MacDonald, 53 and from [[Redditch]], and 63-year-old Margaret Vining, from [[Gloucester]], suffered fatal injuries in the pile-up.
Fairclough, then aged 46, suffered bleeding to the brain and leg injuries. In 1999, he was acquitted at Worcester Crown Court of [[causing death by dangerous driving]] but convicted of [[dangerous driving]] for his role in the collision. His [[Driving licence in the United Kingdom|driving licence]] was suspended for four years and he served three months in [[Hewell (HM Prison)|Hewell Grange prison]]. In November 2001 he successfully brought legal action to have the licence reinstated. A judge ordered him to take an extended driving test.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/archive/2001/11/10/7733366.M42_death_crash_driver_wins_back_his_licence/?ref=arc |title=M42 death crash driver wins back his licence |publisher=Archive.worcesternews.co.uk |date=10 November 2001 |accessdate=25 August 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6I2rGKeHD?url=http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/archive/2001/11/10/7733366.M42_death_crash_driver_wins_back_his_licence/?ref=arc |archivedate=12 July 2013 |deadurl=y |df= }}</ref>
