[[File:Greek American souvlaki grilling at 2011 Greek Festival, Piscataway, New Jersey.jpg|thumb|[[Souvlaki]] grilling at the 2011 [[Greek Festival]] in [[Piscataway, New Jersey]] on May 15, 2011]] The '''Greek Orthodox Church of St. George''' of [[Piscataway, New Jersey]] is the largest Greek congregation in [[New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Encyclopedia of New Jersey |year=2004 |publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]] |quote=The largest of the Greek Orthodox congregations was Saint George of Piscataway. ... |url=http://www2.scc.rutgers.edu/NJEncyclopedia/ |isbn=0-8135-3325-2 |access-date=2011-05-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705104830/http://www2.scc.rutgers.edu/NJEncyclopedia/# |archive-date=2008-07-05 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> In 2016 the congregation celebrated its 100th Anniversary as well as the 43rd anniversary of its [[Greek Festival]].<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Greek festival season is underway: Get your gyro on in Paramus, Piscataway this weekend |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/dining/index.ssf/2011/05/greek_festival_season_is_under.html |quote=John Lyssikatos has been chairman of the festival at St. George Greek Orthodox Church in Piscataway for 13 years, and he says preparations for the May festival start in September. The boneless leg of lamb -- they go through 50 over the course of a weekend -- will be cooked fresh, of course, but baking the Greek sweets for this week's festival has been under way for a couple of months. |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=May 12, 2011 |accessdate=2011-05-15 }}</ref> It's 44th Annual GReek festival takes place May 18 - 21, 2017.
