[[File:Jim LeRoy Bulldog.jpg|thumb|Jim LeRoy in "Bulldog"]] '''Jim LeRoy''' (April 5, 1961 – July 28, 2007) was an [[United States|American]] [[aerobatics]] pilot. He died upon impact in a crash at the Dayton Air Show in Ohio.
==Background== A former [[US Marine Corps]] [[Reconnaissance|Scout]]/[[Sniper]], Jim LeRoy held a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] degree in [[Aeronautical]]/[[Aerospace]] engineering as well as an [[Aircraft Maintenance Technician|Airframe and Powerplant (A&P) license]].
==Stunt flying== Initially flying solo performances, he gained a reputation with his highly energetic aerobatic displays. In 2003, LeRoy joined a daring and successful [[airshow]] troupe, the X-team, who referred to themselves as the [[Masters of Disaster]]. Their performance generally consisted of three pilots flying a simultaneous, chaotic, interweaving aerobatic display through clouds of smoke generated by circling jet-powered trucks below. After two seasons of successful airshows, an accident occurred on July 10, 2005 during a routine performance when [[Jimmy Franklin]] and Bobby Younkin collided in mid-air. Jim LeRoy was not involved in the collision and landed safely.
LeRoy was one of only eleven pilots ever to be awarded both the ''[[Art Scholl]] Showmanship Award'' (2002) and the ''[[Bill Barber (pilot)|Bill Barber]] Award for Showmanship'' (2003). He was also one of only a handful of full-time [[air show]] pilots in the world who actually made his living by performing for air show audiences.
LeRoy also held the following pilot ratings: single-engine, multi-engine, airplane instructor, helicopter, helicopter instructor, instrument instructor and aerobatic competency evaluator.
==Death== {{wikinews|Deadly crash at Dayton, Ohio air show}}
Around 2:15PM [[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|EST]] at the [[Vectren]] [[Dayton Air Show]] at [[Dayton International Airport]] outside [[Dayton, Ohio]], LeRoy crashed his [[Pitts Special|S2S Bulldog II]], while in performance with the X-Team ''Codename: Mary's Lamb'' aerobatics team.<ref>[http://www.whiotv.com/news/13774845/detail.html Dayton Air Show Crash Kills Pilot - News Story - WHIO Dayton<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201231032/http://www.whiotv.com/news/13774845/detail.html |date=2008-12-01 }}</ref> Initial indications showed that he was performing a [[Aerobatic maneuver|1/2 Cuban 8]] and snap rolls on the 45-degree down line,<ref>[http://www.airliners.net/discussions/general_aviation/read.main/3533213/ Jim LeRoy Dies In Airshow Crash — Civil Aviation Forum | Airliners.net<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> but recovered too low to the ground to pull out. He hit the runway at {{convert|200|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, although his vertical speed was only around {{convert|75|mph|km/h|sigfig=2|abbr=on}}; the plane slid {{convert|300|yards|m}} and burst into flames.<ref name=investigation>[http://www.whiotv.com/news/13780478/detail.html Coroner: Pilot Died Instantly - News Story - WHIO Dayton<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222180158/http://www.whiotv.com/news/13780478/detail.html |date=2008-02-22 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.planecrashinfo.com/famous2000s.htm planecrashinfo.com Famous People Who Died in Aviation Accidents: 2000s]</ref> LeRoy was pronounced dead in a military [[MEDEVAC]] helicopter while in transit to [[Miami Valley Hospital]] in [[Dayton, Ohio]]. The [[Forensic pathology|coroner]]'s report states that LeRoy died on impact due to a [[fracture]] of his neck, but that he also was badly burned.<ref name=investigation/>
