{{Infobox recurring event |name = Pittsburgh Renaissance Festival |image = Pittsburgh Renaissance Festival.jpg |alt = |caption = Front gate of the fair |location = [[West Newton, Pennsylvania]] |genre = Renaissance fair |first = 1994 |dates = August - September |attendance = |area = {{convert|20|acre|m2}} |free_label = Stages |free_text = 6 |website = {{url|http://www.pittsburghrenfest.com/}} }} The '''Pittsburgh Renaissance Festival''' is a [[Renaissance fair]] located in [[West Newton, Pennsylvania]]. As of 2011, the fair is in its 17th season. In 2005 the fair had 55,000 attendees.<ref name="abrupt" /> The faire covers {{convert|20|acre|m2}} and, as of 2008, contained six stages.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wong|first=Diana |title=Experience the Renaissance|url=http://thetartan.org/2008/9/8/pillbox/renfest|accessdate=31 December 2010|newspaper=[[The Tartan]]|date=September 8, 2008}}</ref>
The setting for the fair is a village called Morelandshire, sometime between 1533 and 1536.<ref name="rebirth" />
== History == The fair was founded in 1994, and held for three seasons at the Butler County Fairgrounds, while the organizers searched for a suitable property. The present site, an abandoned farm which had subsequently been strip mined and landscaped, was selected for its ideal location and setting, and first hosted the fair in the summer of 1997.<ref name="abrupt">{{cite news|last=Zemba|first=Liz|title=Organizers put abrupt end to Pittsburgh Renaissance Festival|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_460373.html|accessdate=31 December 2010|newspaper=TRIBUNE-REVIEW|date=July 2, 2006 }}</ref> In 2006 the fair was canceled due to lack of financing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poor attendance forces cancellation of renaissance festival|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06184/703051-42.stm|accessdate=31 December 2010|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=July 3, 2006}}</ref> However, a year later, the fair was purchased by Rocky Mountain Festivals<ref>{{cite news|last=McCaffrey|first=Kate |title=Stage Preview: Medieval merriment makes a comeback in West Newton |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07235/811278-325.stm|accessdate=31 December 2010|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=August 23, 2007}}</ref> and was reopened under the direction of the company's CEO.<ref name="rebirth">{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Alice T. |title=Pittsburgh Renaissance Festival gets rebirth|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/dailycourier/news/s_524961.html|accessdate=31 December 2010|newspaper=Tribune-Review|date=August 30, 2007}}</ref>
