{{Infobox ice hockey player | name = René Boileau | image= | image_size = 230px | position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]] | shoots = Left | height_ft = 5 | height_in = 10 | weight_lb = 160 | played_for = [[New York Americans]] | birth_date = {{birth date|1904|5|18|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Pointe-Claire]], [[Quebec]], Canada | death_date = {{death date and age|1969|6|9|1904|5|18}} | death_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada | career_start = 1926 | career_end = 1931 }} '''Joseph Lorenzo Lionel Boileau''' (May 18, 1904 &ndash; June 9, 1969), known as '''René Boileau''', was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] player who played seven games in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) for the [[New York Americans]] and five seasons in various minor-professional leagues. As a publicity stunt, the Americans billed Boileau, a [[French Canadian]], as "the first [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] in the NHL" and claimed his name was Rainy Drinkwater. René is the father of the former NHL hockey player, [[Marc Boileau]].
==Playing career== Boileau, a {{convert|150|lb|abbr=on}} native of [[Pointe-Claire]], [[Quebec]], played his only season in the NHL in [[1925–26 NHL season|1925–26]].<ref name="THN">{{citation |last=Goodhand |first=Glen |year=2005 |title=The Lighter Side of Hockey |periodical=The Hockey News |issn=0018-3016 |page=62}}</ref> Prior to joining the Americans, he played three seasons of amateur hockey in Montreal.<ref name="LOH">{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=12027 |title=Rene Boileau player profile |publisher=Hockey Hall of Fame |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref> Americans manager Tommy Duggan was anxious to promote the first-year Americans and upon signing Boileau used him as part of a publicity stunt.<ref name="THN" /> The Americans official announcement on the signing promoted Boileau under the pseudonym "Rainy Drinkwater" and announced that the French-Canadian player was instead from the Caughnawaga Indian Reservation, and the first Native American to play in the NHL.<ref name="LOH" /> The Canadian press took note of the promotion; former ''[[Toronto Star]]'' sports editor Milt Dunnell said that "He received more ink than [[Sitting Bull]]".<ref name="THN" /> He played only seven games with the Americans, scoring no points.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hockey-reference.com/players/b/boilere01.html |title=Rene Boileau career statistics |publisher=Hockey-Reference |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref>
Boileau spent the next five seasons playing professional hockey with the [[Niagara Falls Cataracts]] of the [[Canadian Professional Hockey League]], [[New Haven Eagles]] of the [[Canadian American Hockey League]] and [[St. Louis Flyers]] of the [[American Hockey Association (1926–1942)|American Hockey Association]]. He then played two seasons of semi-professional hockey in Quebec teams before retiring in 1934.<ref name="LOH" /> His son, [[Marc Boileau|Marc]], played and coached in the NHL.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=12026 |title=Marc Boileau player profile |publisher=Hockey Hall of Fame |accessdate=2010-02-01}}</ref>
